<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-11-11T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-11-11T05:00:00-05:00" n="163" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d163">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/6589:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Ireland</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dublin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-11-11T11:00:00+01:00">November 11, 1940—11 a.m.</date>
                                    <lb/> [Received November 11—8:59 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>100. My telegram number 98, November 8, 6 p.m.<note n="16" xml:id="d163fn16">Not printed.</note> Very confidentially
                                informed that Churchill’s reference to Irish ports was an expression
                                of personal nature of which Cabinet had not been advised. British
                                representative here coincides with views and conclusions set forth
                                in my telegram under reference.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Gray</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>